# Implementation Plan: PRISM Base Mode Configuration

This plan details the technical steps to implement the **PRISM Base Mode**, specifically engineered for extremely resource-constrained edge hardware:
- **GPU**: Nvidia GTX 1050 Ti (4GB total GDDR5 VRAM, ~2.5-3.0GB ML boundary)
- **CPU**: Intel Core i5 4460 (Haswell, 4 Cores, 4 Threads, AVX2)
- **RAM**: 32GB DDR3 (1600 MT/s)
- **SSD**: SATA III (~550 MB/s)

We will introduce a global configuration variable `PRISM_BASE_MODE=true` that activates hardware optimization flags, sequential context caching, dynamic Ollama resident-model interrogation, on-demand GGUF loading, and strict Guardian Agent task pruning.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The transition to Base Mode clamps native `llama-server` instances to a **2048 context window** (down from 4096) and completely disables speculative decoding draft models to keep the VRAM usage strictly within the physical **2.5GB to 3.0GB** boundary of the GTX 1050 Ti. 

> [!NOTE]
> Base Mode implements a **Single-Slot Sequential Runner (SSSR)**. When routing requests to a local GGUF, if the desired model is not loaded in VRAM, the supervisor will dynamically reclaim the slot and load the model on-demand before routing, eliminating duplicate loading/unloading in the UI.

